Iteration 29 is open — `sources/iteration29/` copied from `current` with its assets re-linked to the store — and everything you asked for in this turn is done and verified.

**Gallery.** `iteration028.png` removed. In its place: `iteration028-cv-before.png` (the old Overleaf moderncv one-pager, `assets/cv.pdf`, Spanish) and `iteration028-cv-after.png` (iteration 28's `cv-es.pdf`, rendered before today's rebuild so it shows exactly what 28 produced). Both PNG at the gallery's 1024 width.

**The giant gold word — found and fixed.** The reflective layer (`reflect.js`) rasterises each word onto its span's `getBoundingClientRect()`. A token like `—análisis` or `hello-world` carries a legal break point at the dash, so when the browser breaks the line there, the single span renders as two fragments on two lines — and its bounding rect becomes the union of both: almost column-wide, two lines tall. The raster then stretched the whole word onto that width and centred its baseline in that double-height rect: your giant gold word floating between the lines, revealed whenever a point lit it. The fix is what you prescribed — place the overlay right rather than dodge dashes: when a span has more than one client rect, its text is sliced per line fragment (walking the characters with a Range) and each fragment is rasterised at its own rect with its own width and baseline. Verified with mid-pulse renders of the Spanish page: `todo teórico —` / `análisis`, `escritura—`, and `hello-` / `world` (which fragments at 780px viewport) all light up in register with the ink now.

**CV logo mark.** The closing line now uses `cv-ic-bb.pdf` — the same mark geometry, in the pipes' gold — instead of the black `bb-mark.pdf`, in both languages.

**Top-right stick.** New `cv-stick.pdf`: the frame's top side runs on past the corner and ends in the skills-knot's own down-pointing hook — same shape, a bit longer than the skills salient — its centreline on the top rule's centreline and its tip stopping just short of your name, pointing at it the way the lowest knot's stick points at 'aptitudes'.

**Knot crossings.** You read it exactly right: the pipe entered from above at the bar's ~27% point but the belly re-emerged below at ~46% (the dive x, 19.7 in the art's units). Now the pipe rides that x through the whole knot: it comes down on it, dives under the bar there, the belly re-emerges directly beneath, and the long stick's 45° turn happens sooner — right at that same x — to carry the pipe down on one unbroken line. The art's pipe band moved inside the knot graphics and the tex kern compensates (−10.60pt → −16.98pt), so the pipe stays glued to the margin rule and the frame's corner; the knots' bars (and with them the section names) sit ~6.4pt further left relative to it, which is precisely your "pipes move right as seen from the document".

**The shadow.** The dive shade lightened from `#7a6516` (about half-lit gold) to `#bfa021` (about three-quarters) — a shading the eye reads as the pipe passing under, not a blackening. It applies everywhere the fade is used: knots, both dressed corners, the underpass. Judge it on the rebuilt CVs; if it still reads too dark, dropping it for plain gold is a one-line change (`DARK = GOLD` in `cv-art.js`).

Both CVs rebuilt with `cv-build`, one page each, checked over full renders and close crops of every knot, the stick and the footer. Not done yet, deliberately: `sources/current/` still holds iteration 28 and no gallery pair or interaction files exist for 29 — all of that lands at wrap-up when you call it.


