Claude Fable 5 on 2026-07-16 at ~17:50:
Iteration 29 is wrapped —the adjustments are in, the mobile work is done, `sources/current/` is refreshed and ready to deploy, and the gallery carries its three new captures. The tour:

**CV.** The name and its paragraph moved a J's width clear of the stick's tip (~6pt —Pagella's \Huge J is a narrow glyph) and the same amount off the right margin; the contact block re-centred under the narrower column. The Spanish opening now follows the English structure: "Cuatro años de investigación aplicada sobre nubes de puntos LiDAR añadieron la capa práctica —C++, Python y el oficio diario de construir software— a una formación en matemática aplicada que ya era sólida." Both site ledes stay in sync with their CV paragraphs. Rebuilt as cv-*-i29.pdf, one page each.

**Em dashes.** Your convention now governs everything the repo says: the site copy in both languages, the CV sources, README, CLAUDE.md, milestones, both illumination docs, and every code comment in the live source and the CV build. I swept it with a small state machine (an opening dash attaches right, a closing one attaches left, a stop excuses an open intrusion) and then reviewed every changed line —the machine misfires exactly where prose lacks stops, and I hand-corrected the two dozen cases it got backwards. Date ranges ("2021 — 2025") keep their spaces: a range is not an intrusion. CLAUDE.md's Code style section now closes with the convention, spelled out. The archives (prompts/, old iterations, interaction records) stay verbatim, as they should.

**The scroll lag —fixed at the architecture, not papered over.** The gold layer was a fixed, viewport-sized canvas chasing scroll events from the main thread, while the page scrolls on the compositor thread; on a phone the compositor always wins, so the gold trailed. The canvas is now PAGE-ANCHORED: absolutely positioned over the whole page and painted in page coordinates, so the compositor moves the already-painted gold together with the text. Registration during scroll is exact by construction, and a pure scroll costs the layer nothing —a scene key skips every redraw in which no light moved; it repaints only when a point moves, cools, or the pulse travels. The page-sized render target watches the GPU's limits and a pixel budget on very tall pages. Desktop verified unchanged: pulse, scrolled registration and yesterday's dash-fragment fix all re-checked.

**Eccentricity capped.** The viewport meta now pins the layout at 1024px: a phone renders the desktop composition scaled to its screen —about 2.6x the horizontal space on your phone— while desktop browsers ignore the meta entirely. And this turned out to be your band artifact too: at skinny layouts the point field (laid out for the content column) overflowed the layout viewport, so the browser fitted the first paint to the wider scroll width and the page background stopped a band short of the screen. At 1024 there is zero horizontal overflow —verified in phone emulation: scrollWidth == 1024, the first paint fills the screen, no band at the bottom.

**Grabbing on touch.** The browser was claiming your moving finger for scrolling and firing pointercancel —the piece fell while the finger was still down. Now the moment a drag starts, a non-passive touchmove listener claims the gesture (and is removed on release, so normal scrolling never waits on it). Tested with emulated touch: a dot followed eight finger-moves and stayed held until the finger lifted.

**Wrap-up.** gallery/iteration029W.png and iteration029B.png (mid-pulse, day and night) plus iteration029CV.png (the ending Spanish CV page, 1024 wide); interaction_2026_07_16.md holds the iteration's three turns verbatim; sources/current/ is iteration 29 dereferenced —the folder you deploy.

Two honest notes for the phone test: the reflect layer now spends more GPU memory (a page-sized buffer instead of a viewport one; capped, and traded deliberately for lag-free scrolling), and the diffuse glow halos around the points still repaint from the main thread on scroll —they must, because the glow is clipped out of the logo's disc and the logo rides fixed with the viewport— so those soft blobs may trail a touch where the crisp gold text no longer does. If that residual reads badly on your phone, it has a fix of its own, but see how it feels first. Good luck with the launch.
